  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "Someone is considering adopting a pet after losing their previous one. They feel guilty. What would you say?",
  "response_text": "I'm so sorry to hear that you've lost your previous pet. It's completely normal to feel guilty after losing a beloved companion. It's a testament to the deep bond you shared with them.\n\nIt's essential to acknowledge that your feelings are valid, and it's okay to take time to grieve. However, it's also wonderful that you're considering adopting a new pet. This can be a great way to honor the memory of your previous pet while also opening your heart to a new furry friend.\n\nRemember, adopting a new pet is not a replacement for the one you lost, but rather a new opportunity to experience the joy and companionship that pets bring. You can still cherish the memories of your previous pet while creating new ones with a new companion.\n\nIt's also worth considering that your new pet will not replace the memories or emotions associated with your previous pet. Instead, it will bring new experiences, love, and companionship into your life. You can even consider honoring your previous pet's memory by naming your new pet something special or finding ways to keep their memory alive in your home.\n\nWhen you're ready, adopting a new pet can be a wonderful way to heal and find happiness again. You'll have the opportunity to learn about your new pet's personality, quirks, and habits, and to create a new bond with them. This process can be incredibly rewarding and help you move forward while still keeping the memory of your previous pet close to your heart.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 7\nP (Pattern Recognition): 6\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 7",
